04969nam a22008295i 9783110722765DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021932591  a97831107227657 a10.1515/97831107227652doi  a(DE-B1597)571078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh1 aKazantzidis, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLucretius on Disease :bThe Poetics of Morbidity in ›De rerum natura‹ /cGeorge Kazantzidis. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VII, 211 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ;v11700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Disease and the (Un)Making of the World -- t2 Disease, Closure and the Sense of an Ending -- t3 Disease and the Marvellous. Epilepsy in Book 3 and 6 -- t4 From Callimachean Aesthetics to the Sublime. The Plague in Book 6 -- t5 Afterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex Rerum et Nominum -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe standard view in scholarship is that disease in Lucretius' De rerum natura is mainly a problem to be solved and then dispensed with.However, a closer reading suggests that things are more layered and complex than they appear at first sight: just as morbus causes a radical rearrangement of atoms in the body and makes the patient engage with alternative and up to that point unknown dimensions of the sensible world, so does disease as a theme generate a multiplicity of meanings in the text. The present book argues for a reconsideration of morbus in De rerum natura along those lines: it invites the reader to revisit the topic of disease and reflect on the various, and often contrasting, discourses that unfold around it. More specifically, it illustrates how, apart from calling for therapy, disease, due to its dominant presence in the narrative, transforms at the same time into a concept that is integral both to the poem's philosophical agenda but also to its wider aesthetic concerns as a literary product.The book thus sheds new light on De rerum natura's intense preoccupation with morbus by showing how disease is not exclusively conceived by Lucretius as a blind, obliterating force but is crucially linked to life and meaning-both inside and outside the text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 4aDe rerum natura. 4aGedicht. 4aKrankheit. 4aLukrez. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aDe rerum natura.  aLucretius.  adisease.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2021z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z978311075377608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishz978311075405608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021z97831107538130 cEPUBz97831107229250 cprintz978311072265940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311072276540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110722765423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110722765.jpg  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Ebook Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  a978-3-11-075381-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075405-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL 